anized properly. I should look for the exact paths I need, and I think using Select-String would be helpful to find those residual terms. I’ll focus on gathering all relevant information to ensure everything is structured well.\"}]}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_RqJ4C008Knl0dhNF8d475iVQ|fc_04d04e5a142d912b0169c93370f8e481919fe7f558348982d0","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"$repo='C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory'; cd $repo; $patterns='Branch','BM-','branch','agent','agents','Branches'; Get-ChildItem docs,workspace_mirror -Recurse -File | Select-String -Pattern $patterns | ForEach-Object { \"{0}:{1}: {2}\" -f $_.Path.Replace($repo+'\\',''), $_.LineNumber, $_.Line.Trim() } | Select-Object -First 250","yieldMs":2000,"timeout":25},"partialJson":"{\"command\":\"$repo='C:\\\\Users\\\\User-OEM\\\\Desktop\\\\content-factory\\\\auto_content_factory'; cd $repo; $patterns='Branch','BM-','branch','agent','agents','Branches'; Get-ChildItem docs,workspace_mirror -Recurse -File | Select-String -Pattern $patterns | ForEach-Object { \\\"{0}:{1}: {2}\\\" -f $_.Path.Replace($repo+'\\\\',''), $_.LineNumber, $_.Line.Trim() } | Select-Object -First 250\",\"yieldMs\":2000,\"timeout\":25}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":13052,"output":170,"cacheRead":83328,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":96550,"cost":{"input":0.03263,"output":0.00255,"cacheRead":0.020832,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.056012000000000006}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774793576491,"responseId":"resp_04d04e5a142d912b0169c9336a38b08191ab38f3da86f2416c"}}
{"type":"message","id":"46929fa6","parentId":"1c981e47","timestamp":"2026-03-29T14:13:04.683Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_RqJ4C008Knl0dhNF8d475iVQ|fc_04d04e5a142d912b0169c93370f8e481919fe7f558348982d0","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"docs\\00_CONTEXT.md:9: 2. Nao replicar processos - APRIMORAR (agentes fazem melhor que humanos em tarefas repetitivas)\r\ndocs\\00_CONTEXT.md:10: 3. SaaS entrega ferramenta ($1). Agent as a Service entrega RESULTADO ($6)\r\ndocs\\00_CONTEXT.md:19: 2. O primeiro case de Agents as a Service (documentado como case replicavel)\r\ndocs\\00_CONTEXT.md:70: - Agente \"Tobias\" criado como CEO do departamento de edicao\r\ndocs\\00_CONTEXT.md:75: - AGENTS.md boot sequence actualizado\r\ndocs\\00_CONTEXT.md:81: - Sub-agentes: ~/.openclaw/agents/<agentId>/agent/\r\ndocs\\00_CONTEXT.md:86: - 14 aulas Matt Ganzak digeridas (Security, Multi-agent, Skills, Platform, Cron, Sessions, Tokens, SEO, HeyGen, UGC, Prompt Caching, Update, Autonomous SaaS, Mission Control)\r\ndocs\\00_CONTEXT.md:98: 7. Criar agentes no OpenClaw (PM + VO) e copiar ficheiros\r\ndocs\\00_CONTEXT.md:100: 9. Configurar Telegram Topics para routing por agente\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:7: OpenClaw foi escolhido como framework de agentes. Razoes:\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:12: - Per-agent reasoning controls (modelos diferentes por agente)\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:22: - **Per-agent reasoning controls:** modelo diferente por agente\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:38: - Agentes so acedem a `auto_content_factory/` e `content_factory_v3/output/`\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:41: - API keys via KMS (ja centralizado, nao expostas aos agentes)\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:49: | O que e | Runtime de agentes (o funcionario) | Orquestrador (a empresa) |\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:50: | Multi-agent | Sub-agent spawning | Org charts, hierarquias, reporting |\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:51: | Budget | Agent-level | Per-agent monthly budgets, atomico |\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:52: | Agent-agnostic | Nao (e o agente) | Sim (OpenClaw, Claude Code, scripts, webhooks) |\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:55: - Skip para agora (overkill com <5 agentes)\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:56: - Considerar quando escalar para 5+ agentes com governance\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:62: | Microsoft Agent Framework | Ecossistema Microsoft, menos comunidade indie |\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:63: | Claude Agent SDK | Locked to Anthropic, nao suporta local models |\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:71: - @VadimStrizheus: agente 24/7 que clippa, agenda e posta videos\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:74: - Multi-machine: 5 agentes em 3 maquinas com permission model (per @cmd_alt_ecs)\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:75: - 6 agentes 24/7 com custom skills (per @TechWith_Nova)\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:7: O Lucca propos substituir o workflow engessado por uma equipa de agentes com liberdade editorial. Pontos-chave:\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:14: - Distribui trabalho para os branches abaixo\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:16: ### Branch 1 - Audio\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:23: ### Branch 2 - Dataset / Pesquisa de Imagens\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:24: - Agentes especialistas por tipo: pessoas, objectos, locais, eventos\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:30: ### Branch 3 - Direccao de Cena\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:31: - Recebe relatorio do Branch 2 + cenas + audios do Branch 1\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:35: - Coordena com Branch 2 para verificar se ja existe algo util\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:37: ### Branch 4 - Geracao de Imagens IA\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:41: ### Branch 5 - Edicao (Remotion)\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:48: > \"Ter mais branches com mais agentes e melhor do que menos. Depois retira-se. E melhor ter mais do que menos, principalmente no inicio.\"\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:60: Alguns branches do Lucca misturam as duas:\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:79: #### Camada 2 - Agentes de Decisao Editorial\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:81: **1. Scene Director Agent**\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:86: **2. Visual Research Planner Agent**\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:91: **3. Asset Finder Agents (subagentes operacionais)**\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:99: **4. Asset Judge Agent**\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:104: **5. AI Image Director Agent**\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:109: **6. Scene Composer Agent**\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:115: **7. Typography / Lettering Agent**\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:119: **8. Music & SFX Agent**\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:123: **9. QA / Coherence Agent**\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:124: - OBRIGATORIO - sem ele, multiagente vira delirio\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:130: 2. **Julgamento comparativo** - agente escolhe entre opcoes, nao inventa do zero\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:138: 3. Um agente por ferramenta (fragmentacao burra)\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:139: 4. Um superagente editor (impossivel de depurar)\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:145: 3. **Composicao de cena** - agente decide ordem, duracao, movimentos, overlays\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:154: | Branches | 5 (audio, dataset, direccao, geracao, edicao) | 9 agentes + camada deterministica |\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:155: | Separacao plan/exec | Misturados em alguns branches | Separados explicitamente |\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:157: | Criatividade | \"Dar liberdade aos agentes\" | \"Liberdade dentro de faixas\" |\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:159: | QA | Nao mencionado | Agente obrigatorio |\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:164: 1. Estrutura de branches do Lucca (mais granular, mais agentes)\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:168: 5. QA obrigatorio como ultimo agente\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:169: 6. Per-agent model routing\r\ndocs\\03_PIPELINE_MAP.md:16: | **Divisao em cenas (Screenplay Agent)** | **CREATIVE** | parallel_screenplay.py (GPT-4.1-mini) |\r\ndocs\\03_PIPELINE_MAP.md:77: | Phase 5 | TSX validation + auto-fix | DETERMINISTIC + CREATIVE (fix agent) |\r\ndocs\\03_PIPELINE_MAP.md:92: ## Operacoes CREATIVE (candidatas a agentes)\r\ndocs\\05_MULTI_MACHINE_ARCHITECTURE.md:6: - **M1**: OpenClaw completo (Gateway + control plane + web UI + agentes)\r\ndocs\\05_MULTI_MACHINE_ARCHITECTURE.md:19: 1. Agente no M1 decide: \"preciso gerar 80 imagens para video X\"\r\ndocs\\05_MULTI_MACHINE_ARCHITECTURE.md:27: - O \"peso\" e nos agentes LLM - mas esses sao API calls (Gemini, OpenAI), nao compute local\r\ndocs\\05_MULTI_MACHINE_ARCHITECTURE.md:41: - @TechWith_Nova: 6 agentes 24/7 num unico OpenClaw\r\ndocs\\06_MODEL_STRATEGY.md:5: ### Main Agent (Orquestrador + conversacao)\r\ndocs\\06_MODEL_STRATEGY.md:7: - **Razao:** melhor custo-beneficio para agente principal 24/7, sem billing por token\r\ndocs\\06_MODEL_STRATEGY.md:10: ### Sub-agentes (tarefas especificas)\r\ndocs\\06_MODEL_STRATEGY.md:28: | ChatGPT Pro (main agent) | $200/mo |\r\ndocs\\06_MODEL_STRATEGY.md:29: | Anthropic API (sub-agentes quando necessario) | ~$50/mo |\r\ndocs\\06_MODEL_STRATEGY.md:38: - Claude fica como opcao para sub-agentes via API key\r\ndocs\\07_BRAINDUMP_OPENCLAW.md:19: O sistema actual funciona assim: para cada conta, um humano (eu, Lucca, junto com o Claude Code) configurou uma �nica vez todo o estilo de edi��o - quais prompts os agentes de IA usam, que tipo de imagens s�o geradas, que estilo de lettering aparece, que tipo de m�sica toca, como as cenas s�o compostas. Depois dessa configura��o, o pipeline gera v�deos automaticamente para diferentes scripts e temas.\r\ndocs\\07_BRAINDUMP_OPENCLAW.md:23: Hoje temos agentes de IA dentro do pipeline - eles dividem cenas, escolhem imagens, planeiam m�sica. Mas esses agentes seguem instru��es fixas definidas nos prompts. N�o tomam decis�es criativas verdadeiras. N�o adaptam o estilo baseado no conte�do. N�o pensam \"esta cena pede algo diferente\".\r\ndocs\\07_BRAINDUMP_OPENCLAW.md:27: O objectivo final � ter uma equipa de agentes aut�nomos que funcionem como um time real de editores de v�deo - onde cada v�deo tem o seu pr�prio processo criativo �nico. Agentes que:\r\ndocs\\07_BRAINDUMP_OPENCLAW.md:98: Estou a desenvolver a documenta��o e arquitectura para transformar o departamento de edi��o de v�deo num sistema aut�nomo de agentes. Este trabalho est� a ser feito em conjunto com o Claude Code (Anthropic), que roda nesta mesma m�quina e tem acesso aos mesmos ficheiros.\r\ndocs\\07_BRAINDUMP_OPENCLAW.md:104: O objectivo � definir uma hierarquia de agentes especializados - cada um com papel, modelo de IA e ferramentas espec�ficas - que consigam operar o departamento de edi��o de v�deo com cada vez mais autonomia e criatividade.\r\ndocs\\07_BRAINDUMP_OPENCLAW.md:108: - Tu (agente principal): actualmente em Sonnet 4.6 via API Key Anthropic. Ap�s o onboarding, migraremos para GPT-5.4 via ChatGPT Pro OAuth.\r\ndocs\\07_BRAINDUMP_OPENCLAW.md:109: - Sub-agentes simples: modelos locais via Ollama (Qwen 3.5 9B, Qwen3 14B) - custo $0\r\ndocs\\07_BRAINDUMP_OPENCLAW.md:110: - Sub-agentes que precisam de qualidade: Claude Sonnet/Opus via API key Anthropic, ou modelos custo-eficientes via OpenRouter (DeepSeek, MiniMax, Gemini Flash, entre outros - dependendo da tarefa)\r\ndocs\\07_BRAINDUMP_OPENCLAW.md:126: Baseado em tudo o que sabes sobre mim e sobre a Content Factory, o que mais precisas saber para me ajudar a transformar este departamento num sistema aut�nomo de agentes?\r\ndocs\\08_SECURITY_HARDENING.md:207: 1. **\"Eu uso zero skills de terceiros. O meu agente roda com skills que EU fiz.\"**\r\ndocs\\08_SECURITY_HARDENING.md:227: - Snyk Labs: \"Escaping the Agent: On Ways to Bypass OpenClaw's Security Sandbox\"\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:11: Agentes n�o s�o c�digo. S�o:\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:14: - Cada agente com papel, modelo e ferramentas espec�ficas\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:15: - Comunica��o entre agentes via artefactos estruturados (JSON, markdown)\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:16: - **Isolamento de contexto**: cada agente s� carrega os .md da sua pasta\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:33: ��� agents/\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:60: �       �   ��� agents/\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:71: �       �   ��� agents/\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:80: �       �   ��� agents/\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:90: �       �   ��� AGENTS.md\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:94: �       �   ��� agents/\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:109: �       �   ��� agents/\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:117: �       �   ��� agents/\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:127: �       �   ��� agents/\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:135: �       �   ��� agents/\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:145: �       �   ��� agents/\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:154: �           ��� agents/\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:194: �   Pasta: agents/tobias/                     �\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:207: �   Pasta: agents/production_manager/         �\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:220: �   Pasta: agents/video_orchestrator/         �\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:245: �  Pasta: agents/setores/sNN_nome/                       �\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:259: �  - Pasta: agents/setores/sNN_nome/agents/nome_agente/  �\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:284: FASE 1 (agora):      Tobias + Production Manager    = 2 agentes\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:285: FASE 2 (funcionar):  + primeiros Supervisores        = 5 agentes\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:286: FASE 3 (escalar):    + restantes Supervisores        = 12 agentes\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:287: FASE 4 (completo):   + operadores individuais        = ~60+ agentes\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:294: - Modelos por agente: a definir (excepto Tobias = GPT-5.4 Pro)\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:331: | 26 Mar 2026 | Implementa��o incremental: 2 -> 5 -> 12 -> 60+ agentes |\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:334: | 26 Mar 2026 | Workspace OpenClaw entendido: default em ~/.openclaw/workspace/, sub-agentes em ~/.openclaw/agents/<id>/ |\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:336: | 26 Mar 2026 | AGENTS.md boot sequence actualizado: l� IDENTITY + MISSION + CONTEXT + TASKS no startup |\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:340: | 28 Mar 2026 | Terminologia actualizada: \"branches\" -> \"setores\", \"Branch Managers\" -> \"Supervisores de Setor (SM-S#)\", \"agentes\" -> \"operadores\" |\r\ndocs\\10_PRODUCTION_MANAGER.md:227: **Localiza��o oficial**: `~/.openclaw/agents/<pm_agent_id>/agent/`\r\ndocs\\10_PRODUCTION_MANAGER.md:233: | AGENTS.md | Boot sequence |\r\ndocs\\11_VIDEO_ORCHESTRATOR.md:35: O VO � o �nico agente abaixo do Tobias que **comunica directamente com Tobias e com o Lucca**. Isto porque:\r\ndocs\\11_VIDEO_ORCHESTRATOR.md:178: **Localiza��o oficial**: `~/.openclaw/agents/<vo_agent_id>/agent/`\r\ndocs\\11_VIDEO_ORCHESTRATOR.md:184: | AGENTS.md | Boot sequence |\r\ndocs\\11_VIDEO_ORCHESTRATOR.md:231: | 26 Mar 2026 | VO comunica directamente com Tobias E Lucca (�nico agente abaixo do CEO com este privil�gio) |\r\ndocs\\12_VIDEO_DIRECTORY_STRUCTURE.md:151: �   ��� agent_calls/                    <- input/output de cada chamada de operador\r\ndocs\\12_VIDEO_DIRECTORY_STRUCTURE.md:181: Cada chamada de operador gera um log em `logs/agent_calls/`:\r\ndocs\\12_VIDEO_DIRECTORY_STRUCTURE.md:184: \"agent\": \"scene_director\",\r\ndocs\\12_VIDEO_DIRECTORY_STRUCTURE.md:208: \"agent\": \"scene_director\",\r\ndocs\\12_VIDEO_DIRECTORY_STRUCTURE.md:253: | 26 Mar 2026 | Cada operador loga input/output em logs/agent_calls/ |\r\ndocs\\branches\\01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md:21: - **Fun��o**: Coordena o fluxo dos 3 agentes + 2 skills\r\ndocs\\branches\\01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md:23: - Gere retries (max 3x por agente)\r\ndocs\\branches\\01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md:25: - Gere contexto entre agentes (limpa contexto entre passos para scripts longos 20min+)\r\ndocs\\branches\\01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md:171: \"agent\": \"scene_director\",\r\ndocs\\branches\\01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md:201: |-- logs/agent_calls/\r\ndocs\\branches\\01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md:223: Cada idioma define as suas pr�prias regras. O agente `tts_polish` l� estas regras do YAML e aplica-as - n�o existem prompts separados por idioma (.txt). Um �nico agente, m�ltiplas configs.\r\ndocs\\branches\\01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md:231: 2. **Itera��o com valida��o (n�o retry cego)** - Cada agente � validado por uma skill determin�stica. Se falha, o SM sabe exactamente o que corrigir.\r\ndocs\\branches\\01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md:233: 3. **Correc��o cir�rgica (s� cenas afectadas)** - Se a valida��o falha em 2 de 30 cenas, s� essas 2 voltam ao agente. Reduz custo e tempo.\r\ndocs\\branches\\01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md:235: 4. **Memory individual por agente** - Cada agente tem o seu `MEMORY.md`, acumula padr�es e erros frequentes. Aprendizagem persistente.\r\ndocs\\branches\\01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md:237: 5. **Config por idioma (YAML), n�o prompt por idioma** - Um agente, muitos idiomas. As regras espec�ficas (tts_polish_rules, scene_words_range) v�m do YAML do canal.\r\ndocs\\branches\\01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md:243: 8. **Gest�o de contexto para scripts longos (20min+)** - SM-S1 limpa contexto entre passos para evitar overflow. Cada agente recebe s� o que precisa.\r\ndocs\\branches\\01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md:253: | Screenplay | Prompt fixo .txt, executa 1x, sem valida��o | Agente com RULES + EXAMPLES, itera, valida vs original |\r\ndocs\\branches\\01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md:254: | TTS Polish | Prompt fixo por idioma, executa 1x | Agente Qwen + regras YAML + valida��o |\r\ndocs\\branches\\01_PRE_PRODUCTION.md:259: | Aprendizagem | Zero | MEMORY.md por agente |\r\ndocs\\branches\\02_AUDIO.md:19: - **Fun��o**: Coordena 1 sub-agente + 3 skills\r\ndocs\\branches\\02_AUDIO.md:27: ### audio_validator (sub-agente LLM)\r\ndocs\\branches\\02_AUDIO.md:183: |-- logs/agent_calls/\r\ndocs\\branches\\02_AUDIO.md:252: | Aprendizagem | Zero | MEMORY.md por agente (audio_validator aprende padr�es) |\r\ndocs\\branches\\02_AUDIO.md:268: | 26 Mar 2026 | audio_validator � agente Qwen (n�o skill Python) - evita regenera��es desnecess�rias |\r\ndocs\\branches\\02_AUDIO.md:269: | 26 Mar 2026 | tts_generator e timing_extractor s�o skills Python (n�o agentes LLM) |\r\ndocs\\branches\\03_VISUAL_PLANNING.md:242: \"agent\": \"character_identifier\",\r\ndocs\\branches\\03_VISUAL_PLANNING.md:347: ��� logs/agent_calls/\r\ndocs\\branches\\03_VISUAL_PLANNING.md:372: 8. **Memory individual por agente** - Cada identificador tem o seu `MEMORY.md`, acumula padr�es e erros frequentes. Aprendizagem persistente.\r\ndocs\\branches\\03_VISUAL_PLANNING.md:376: 10. **Futuro: adicionar mais identificadores facilmente** - SM s� activa os relevantes via entity_focus. Adicionar um novo identificador � criar o agente + adicionar a chave no YAML.\r\ndocs\\branches\\03_VISUAL_PLANNING.md:384: | Identifica��o visual | 1 agente generalista (entity_extractor) | 8 identificadores especializados em paralelo |\r\ndocs\\branches\\04_ASSET_RESEARCH.md:446: \"agent\": \"character_searcher\",\r\ndocs\\branches\\04_ASSET_RESEARCH.md:466: \"agent\": \"asset_advisor\",\r\ndocs\\branches\\04_ASSET_RESEARCH.md:525: ��� logs/agent_calls/\r\ndocs\\branches\\04_ASSET_RESEARCH.md:585: | 29 Mar 2026 | Novo agente: asset_advisor (GPT-5.4 mini OAuth) analisa assets e preenche tags + how_to_use |\r\ndocs\\branches\\05_VISUAL_DIRECTION.md:22: - Gere retries (max 3x por agente)\r\ndocs\\branches\\05_VISUAL_DIRECTION.md:24: - **Ficheiros**: `IDENTITY.md`, `RULES.md`, `CONTEXT.md`, `TOOLS.md`, `AGENTS.md`, `MEMORY.md`\r\ndocs\\branches\\05_VISUAL_DIRECTION.md:33: - **Ficheiros**: `AGENTS.md`, `PROMPT.md`, `RULES.md`, `TOOLS.md`, `MEMORY.md`\r\ndocs\\branches\\05_VISUAL_DIRECTION.md:43: - **Ficheiros**: `AGENTS.md`, `PROMPT.md`, `RULES.md`, `TOOLS.md`, `MEMORY.md`\r\ndocs\\branches\\05_VISUAL_DIRECTION.md:53: - **Ficheiros**: `AGENTS.md`, `PROMPT.md`, `RULES.md`, `TOOLS.md`, `MEMORY.md`\r\ndocs\\branches\\05_VISUAL_DIRECTION.md:180: ## Contexto por Agente (tamanho controlado)\r\ndocs\\branches\\05_VISUAL_DIRECTION.md:182: | Agente | Input | Tokens aprox. |\r\ndocs\\branches\\05_VISUAL_DIRECTION.md:294: \"agent\": \"narrative_segmenter\",\r\ndocs\\branches\\05_VISUAL_DIRECTION.md:312: \"agent\": \"asset_matcher\",\r\ndocs\\branches\\05_VISUAL_DIRECTION.md:330: \"agent\": \"visual_director\",\r\ndocs\\branches\\05_VISUAL_DIRECTION.md:373: ��� logs/agent_calls/\r\ndocs\\branches\\05_VISUAL_DIRECTION.md:386: 2. **Nenhum agente recebe tudo** -- SM divide screenplay em chunks. Segmenter recebe ~30 cenas. Matcher recebe 1 bloco + lista resumida. Director recebe 1 bloco + kit filtrado. Contexto controlado.\r\ndocs\\branches\\06_IMAGE_GENERATION.md:19: - Solucao: automacao de browser. Agentes navegam nas plataformas como se fossem humanos\r\ndocs\\branches\\06_IMAGE_GENERATION.md:34: - **Ficheiros**: `IDENTITY.md`, `RULES.md`, `CONTEXT.md`, `TOOLS.md`, `AGENTS.md`, `MEMORY.md`\r\ndocs\\branches\\06_IMAGE_GENERATION.md:44: - **Ficheiros**: `AGENTS.md`, `PROMPT.md`, `RULES.md`, `TOOLS.md`, `MEMORY.md`\r\ndocs\\branches\\06_IMAGE_GENERATION.md:54: - Detalhes de implementacao (agente ou skill, qual plataforma) a definir\r\ndocs\\branches\\06_IMAGE_GENERATION.md:142: - **Agente vision** para passos que variam (avaliar resultados, escolher o melhor)\r\ndocs\\branches\\06_IMAGE_GENERATION.md:143: - **Fallback**: se script falha -> agente vision tenta completar\r\ndocs\\branches\\06_IMAGE_GENERATION.md:155: 5. **portrait_manager**: agente ou skill, qual plataforma, que modelo\r\ndocs\\branches\\06_IMAGE_GENERATION.md:224: \"agent\": \"SM-S6\",\r\ndocs\\branches\\06_IMAGE_GENERATION.md:243: \"agent\": \"skill_browser_freepik\",\r\ndocs\\branches\\06_IMAGE_GENERATION.md:313: ��� logs/agent_calls/\r\ndocs\\branches\\07_SCENE_COMPOSITION.md:10: S7 e responsavel por todos os componentes VISUAIS do Remotion. Recebe `compiled_visual_brief.json` do S5 + assets finais do S6. Produz ficheiros `.tsx` para animacao, transicao, composicao de layers e efeitos visuais. Padrao: agente decide (JSON dentro de catalogo) -> skill Python gera `.tsx` a partir de templates. Agentes NUNCA escrevem TSX.\r\ndocs\\branches\\07_SCENE_COMPOSITION.md:21: - **Funcao**: Coordena os 4 planners. Gera slim JSONs customizados por agente. Recebe outputs JSON dos planners. Despacha skills Python para geracao de `.tsx`. Faz merge final dos batches em layer files.\r\ndocs\\branches\\07_SCENE_COMPOSITION.md:22: - Gere retries (max 3x por agente)\r\ndocs\\branches\\07_SCENE_COMPOSITION.md:24: - **Ficheiros**: `IDENTITY.md`, `RULES.md`, `CONTEXT.md`, `TOOLS.md`, `AGENTS.md`, `MEMORY.md`\r\ndocs\\branches\\07_SCENE_COMPOSITION.md:33: - **Ficheiros**: `AGENTS.md`, `PROMPT.md`, `RULES.md`, `TOOLS.md`, `MEMORY.md`\r\ndocs\\branches\\07_SCENE_COMPOSITION.md:44: - **Ficheiros**: `AGENTS.md`, `PROMPT.md`, `RULES.md`, `TOOLS.md`, `MEMORY.md`\r\ndocs\\branches\\07_SCENE_COMPOSITION.md:54: - **Ficheiros**: `AGENTS.md`, `PROMPT.md`, `RULES.md`, `TOOLS.md`, `MEMORY.md`\r\ndocs\\branches\\07_SCENE_COMPOSITION.md:64: - **Ficheiros**: `AGENTS.md`, `PROMPT.md`, `RULES.md`, `TOOLS.md`, `MEMORY.md`\r\ndocs\\branches\\07_SCENE_COMPOSITION.md:465: ## Contexto por Agente (tamanho controlado)\r\ndocs\\branches\\07_SCENE_COMPOSITION.md:467: | Agente | Input | Tokens aprox. |\r\ndocs\\branches\\07_SCENE_COMPOSITION.md:620: ��� logs/agent_calls/\r\ndocs\\branches\\07_SCENE_COMPOSITION.md:657: \"agent\": \"SM-S7\",\r\ndocs\\branches\\07_SCENE_COMPOSITION.md:677: \"agent\": \"animation_planner\",\r\ndocs\\branches\\07_SCENE_COMPOSITION.md:699: \"agent\": \"python_skills\",\r\ndocs\\branches\\07_SCENE_COMPOSITION.md:716: \"agent\": \"SM-S7\",\r\ndocs\\branches\\07_SCENE_COMPOSITION.md:735: 1. **Agente NUNCA escreve TSX** -- Planners decidem em JSON dentro de um catalogo fixo. Skills Python geram `.tsx` a partir de templates parametrizados. Zero risco de TSX invalido.\r\ndocs\\branches\\07_SCENE_COMPOSITION.md:737: 2. **Slim JSONs customizados por agente** -- Cada planner recebe APENAS a informacao que precisa. animation_planner nao sabe de VFX. transition_planner nao sabe de composicoes. Contexto minimo = respostas melhores.\r\ndocs\\branches\\07_SCENE_COMPOSITION.md:828: | 29 Mar 2026 | Agentes NUNCA escrevem TSX -- decidem em JSON, skills Python geram .tsx |\r\ndocs\\branches\\08_POST_PRODUCTION.md:10: S8 e responsavel por todos os componentes de AUDIO (excepto narracao) e TEXTO do Remotion. Musica, efeitos sonoros e letterings. Padrao: agente decide (JSON) -> Audio Resolver valida/injeta paths -> skill Python gera .tsx. LLMs NUNCA controlam paths ou volumes.\r\ndocs\\branches\\08_POST_PRODUCTION.md:22: - Gere retries (max 3x por agente)\r\ndocs\\branches\\08_POST_PRODUCTION.md:24: - **Ficheiros**: `IDENTITY.md`, `RULES.md`, `CONTEXT.md`, `TOOLS.md`, `AGENTS.md`, `MEMORY.md`\r\ndocs\\branches\\08_POST_PRODUCTION.md:33: - **Ficheiros**: `AGENTS.md`, `PROMPT.md`, `RULES.md`, `TOOLS.md`, `MEMORY.md`\r\ndocs\\branches\\08_POST_PRODUCTION.md:42: - **Ficheiros**: `AGENTS.md`, `PROMPT.md`, `RULES.md`, `TOOLS.md`, `MEMORY.md`\r\ndocs\\branches\\08_POST_PRODUCTION.md:54: - **Ficheiros**: `AGENTS.md`, `PROMPT.md`, `RULES.md`, `TOOLS.md`, `MEMORY.md`\r\ndocs\\branches\\08_POST_PRODUCTION.md:226: ## Contexto por Agente (tamanho controlado)\r\ndocs\\branches\\08_POST_PRODUCTION.md:228: | Agente | Input | Tokens aprox. |\r\ndocs\\branches\\08_POST_PRODUCTION.md:676: ��� logs/agent_calls/\r\ndocs\\branches\\08_POST_PRODUCTION.md:708: \"agent\": \"SM-S8\",\r\ndocs\\branches\\08_POST_PRODUCTION.md:758: \"agent\": \"audio_resolver\",\r\ndocs\\branches\\09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md:10: S9 e o controlo de qualidade tecnico + montagem final + render. Recebe `.tsx` de S7 (visual) e S8 (audio/texto), revisa cada componente com reviewers especializados, merge em projecto Remotion completo, compila, renderiza em chunks paralelos. Cada componente `.tsx` e revisado por um agente LLM especializado ANTES do merge - erros sao corrigidos aqui, nao depois do render.\r\ndocs\\branches\\09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md:24: - **Ficheiros**: `IDENTITY.md`, `RULES.md`, `CONTEXT.md`, `TOOLS.md`, `AGENTS.md`, `MEMORY.md`\r\ndocs\\branches\\09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md:33: - **Ficheiros**: `AGENTS.md`, `PROMPT.md`, `RULES.md`, `TOOLS.md`, `MEMORY.md`\r\ndocs\\branches\\09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md:43: - **Ficheiros**: `AGENTS.md`, `PROMPT.md`, `RULES.md`, `TOOLS.md`, `MEMORY.md`\r\ndocs\\branches\\09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md:53: - **Ficheiros**: `AGENTS.md`, `PROMPT.md`, `RULES.md`, `TOOLS.md`, `MEMORY.md`\r\ndocs\\branches\\09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md:63: - **Ficheiros**: `AGENTS.md`, `PROMPT.md`, `RULES.md`, `TOOLS.md`, `MEMORY.md`\r\ndocs\\branches\\09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md:73: - **Ficheiros**: `AGENTS.md`, `PROMPT.md`, `RULES.md`, `TOOLS.md`, `MEMORY.md`\r\ndocs\\branches\\09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md:83: - **Ficheiros**: `AGENTS.md`, `PROMPT.md`, `RULES.md`, `TOOLS.md`, `MEMORY.md`\r\ndocs\\branches\\09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md:93: - **Ficheiros**: `AGENTS.md`, `PROMPT.md`, `RULES.md`, `TOOLS.md`, `MEMORY.md`\r\ndocs\\branches\\09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md:102: - **Ficheiros**: `AGENTS.md`, `PROMPT.md`, `RULES.md`, `TOOLS.md`, `MEMORY.md`\r\ndocs\\branches\\09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md:949: ��� logs/agent_calls/\r\ndocs\\branches\\09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md:989: \"agent\": \"SM-S9\",\r\ndocs\\branches\\09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md:1008: \"agent\": \"animation_reviewer\",\r\ndocs\\branches\\09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md:1029: \"agent\": \"lettering_reviewer\",\r\ndocs\\branches\\09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md:1056: \"agent\": \"python_skills\",\r\ndocs\\branches\\09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md:1083: \"agent\": \"compile_test\",\r\ndocs\\branches\\09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md:1100: \"agent\": \"compile_test + render_fix\",\r\ndocs\\branches\\09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md:1135: \"agent\": \"chunked_render\",\r\ndocs\\branches\\09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md:1157: \"agent\": \"SM-S9\",\r\ndocs\\branches\\09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md:1178: ## Contexto por Agente (tamanho controlado)\r\ndocs\\branches\\09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md:1180: | Agente | Input | Tokens aprox. |\r\ndocs\\branches\\09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md:1198: 2. **Cada reviewer e especialista no SEU componente** -- animation_reviewer so sabe de animacoes. sfx_reviewer so sabe de efeitos sonoros. Especializacao produz melhores revisoes do que um agente generico que tenta revisar tudo.\r\ndocs\\branches\\09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md:1200: 3. **Python detecta, agente LLM corrige com contexto** -- tsx_validator e overlap_detector sao deterministicos e rapidos ($0). Detectam problemas mecanicos (ranges, tipos, sobreposicoes). Mas a CORRECCAO precisa de contexto narrativo (porque esta animacao existe, porque este lettering e importante). Agente LLM corrige com reasoning.\r\ndocs\\branches\\09_ASSEMBLY_RENDER.md:1289: | 29 Mar 2026 | Python detecta overlaps, agente LLM corrige com contexto |\r\ndocs\\branches\\10_FINALIZATION.md:24: - **Ficheiros**: `IDENTITY.md`, `RULES.md`, `CONTEXT.md`, `TOOLS.md`, `AGENTS.md`, `MEMORY.md`\r\ndocs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Advanced Telegram Workflow\\lesson-notes.md:120: - **Self-configuration:** The OpenClaw can modify its own Telegram bot settings when asked, demonstrating the agent's ability to manage its own infrastructure.\r\ndocs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Fix ANY OpenClaw Issue\\lesson-notes.md:11: When your OpenClaw breaks (stops responding, won't load, config errors), the universal fix is: navigate to your OpenClaw folder in the terminal, open Claude Code (or Codex) inside it, describe the issue with context, and let the coding agent fix the config. This has a reported 100% success rate.\r\ndocs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Fix ANY OpenClaw Issue\\lesson-notes.md:26: | `memory.md` | Your agent's memories and learned context |\r\ndocs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Fix ANY OpenClaw Issue\\lesson-notes.md:28: | `soul.md` | Your agent's personality and behavior rules |\r\ndocs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Fix ANY OpenClaw Issue\\lesson-notes.md:38: 2. Before OpenClaw officially supports it, you ask your agent to switch to the new model\r\ndocs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Fix ANY OpenClaw Issue\\lesson-notes.md:42: Other causes include any manual or agent-initiated change to config files that introduces invalid values.\r\ndocs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Fix ANY OpenClaw Issue\\lesson-notes.md:49: Breathe. Your agent is not dead. Your memories, soul, and persona files are intact. Only the config is broken.\r\ndocs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Fix ANY OpenClaw Issue\\lesson-notes.md:97: This opens a coding agent **with full access to your OpenClaw folder**.\r\ndocs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Fix ANY OpenClaw Issue\\lesson-notes.md:101: Give the coding agent a clear prompt. Example:\r\ndocs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Fix ANY OpenClaw Issue\\lesson-notes.md:128: - Claude Code / Codex is a powerful coding agent that can read, understand, and edit these files\r\ndocs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Fix ANY OpenClaw Issue\\lesson-notes.md:137: | \"My agent is dead\" | No. Your agent is just markdown files. Config broke, agent is fine. |\r\ndocs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Fix ANY OpenClaw Issue\\lesson-notes.md:139: | \"I can never get it back\" | No. Even in the worst case, copy `memory.md`, `soul.md`, `user.md` into a fresh OpenClaw install and you have the exact same agent. |\r\ndocs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Fix ANY OpenClaw Issue\\lesson-notes.md:152: 5. Your agent will be identical -- same personality, same memories, same everything\r\ndocs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Fix ANY OpenClaw Issue\\lesson-notes.md:195: The entire lesson boils down to one simple workflow: **when OpenClaw breaks, use Claude Code (or Codex) to fix it from inside the OpenClaw folder.** The agent's identity, memories, and personality are just markdown files that survive any config corruption. The only thing that breaks is the config, and a coding agent can fix configs trivially. This method has a reported 100% success rate across all types of OpenClaw issues.\r\ndocs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Fix ANY OpenClaw Issue\\transcription.txt:1: So I want to real quick go over debugging anything that might happen in your OpenClaw. I hear this a lot. My OpenClaw broke. It's not working anymore. I can't talk to my agent. It is a very stress inducing moment. I understand it's happened to me multiple times. You're talking to your OpenClaw. You have to do something. It changes the config and all of a sudden it will not respond anymore. Well I have a fix that has worked with 100% certainty with me. 100% of the issues I've found that are broken OpenClaw, this has fixed it. It is very, very simple. For those that do not know, every single file and folder related to OpenClaw is local on your computer. It lives in the root of your computer, right? So my root is my name here and then inside here is a folder called Claude. This is going to be Claude for you if you did this back in the Claudebot days. If you joined in the OpenClaw days, it'll probably say OpenClaw. This is where every file and folder lives that configures your open claw. By default, it is hidden. It is a hidden folder. So what you're going to need to do is go to your root folder in your finder and then hit command shift period on your keyboard. What that'll do is reveal all the hidden files and folders revealing your open claw folder. This is where your memories live, your persona, your soul, all of that lives inside there. All the config files are inside this folder. Now when you have your OpenClaw do something like change its model or change its config if it breaks something or does something wrong the entire thing stops working So we need to fix whatever broken your config file Most of the time this happens when you switching models So a lot of times anthropic will come out with a new model, sonnet four, six, opus four, six, whatever. And before open claw officially supports it, you go and you try to make it. So it uses that new model, which is totally fine. I do it. I do it all the time. The issue is sometimes OpenClaw changes its config file wrong and breaks itself. It will try to go to the new model and it will just do it wrong and it breaks itself and you can't talk to it anymore. So here's what you need to do when something like this happens, when your OpenClaw is no longer responding or really any other problem you're running into when it comes to OpenClaw and it's not working correctly. First thing you do is take a deep breath because I understand how stressful and anxious it can make you when things break. When your best friend stops talking to you, I get it. Take a deep breath. Then what you want to do is open up your terminal. So you go in here. What you want to do in your terminal is find that clawed folder, right? So you want to go into that folder. So if you type LS and hit enter, it will list every file and folder of the folder you're inside of. Typically you start off at the root folder here. If you see your open claw folder, whether it's clawed or open claw, what you want to do is you want to CD into it. CD-ing into it basically makes you go into that folder in your terminal. So you can do CD, then you start typing the name of whatever it is, OpenClaw or Claude. You can hit tab to autocomplete and then you hit enter and it goes into your folder and now you can see you know your name of your computer and then Claude or OpenClaude will be the next thing there That means you in the folder If you hit LS, you can see everything that's in that folder. So first, get to the root folder. You can do this by doing, you know, typically if this is your first time in a terminal, it'll have you in the root folder. But if you're deeper in, all you need to do is do CD space dot dot that backs you up, that takes you a level higher in the hierarchy. doing that until you go to the root. And then once you're in the root CD into the open claw folder, right? Boom. We're in here now, right? You can see the computer and the name of the folder. Now, what we're going to do is go into Claude code. So either Claude code or Codex, whichever one you're subscribed to. So you're going to type in Claude, C-L-A-U-D-E for Claude code or Codex for Codex. And that will open up Claude code or Codex in your open claw folder. So either one works they're both going to work well now and now you have a coding agent a very smart coding agent that is going to fix your issue so whatever your issue is you go hey you're in my open claw folder I'm having this issue dot dot dot then you describe your issue it's not responding anymore give it context to say I was trying to switch the model I was trying to change this I went in and I tried to change the config file myself whatever it is you list that out then you hit enter and ClaudeCode will fix it. It has fixed it with 100% success rate for me. 100% success rate this has worked, right? So you just describe whatever it is, ClaudeCode will go research OpenClaw on the internet understand how it works and then go in and figure out what you did wrong and fix it for you This should make it work There is no way to break this other than messing with a config file, and config files are easily fixable. Breaking your OpenClaw does not delete it, does not ruin your memories, does not make it so you'll never get it back again. Your agent is not dead because everything lives in your folder, right? In that OpenClaw folder. So you see memory.md, You see user.md. You see soul.md. Those don't break when your OpenClaw stops working. That's just a markdown file that describes everything. That's all your OpenClaw is. Your config just broke and it will fix the config and you'll be right back to normal. Even if somehow the whole thing was permanently broken, it doesn't matter. You can just copy your memory.md file, your soul.md file, put it in a new OpenClaw. It'll be the exact same agent, the exact same OpenClaw. So I promise you, you'll be all right. This should work with basically 100% certainty. If this doesn't work, feel free to post in the community and we'll try to fix it for you. But this should work pretty much every time. I mean I have messed with everything, broken everything, and this has fixed it every single time. Make sure you give it enough context and CloudCode or Codex should be able to fix it. If you're not familiar with CloudCode or don't have it installed, I have an entire CloudCode masterclass. You should take that. It's awesome. Everyone should learn how to use CloudCode. There's so much value in it. still with open claw. There's so much value from learning clawed code. So make sure to take that as well. If you haven't, and I will see you in the next video.\r\ndocs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Local Models\\transcription.txt:1: Local AI is a very important topic because I believe this is the future of OpenClaw. Everyone running their own local models, powering their own AI agent. And so I think this is very important to learn, especially early on before this has even gotten big and before many people are doing it. Because if you can learn this now, you can get ahead of the trends and you can unlock power with OpenClaw that most people do not have, which will give you an advantage. you an advantage. Now what are local AI models? Local AI models are just models that run on your computer. So whatever computer have models that run on it could be your computer, could be your iPhone, could be any device you have. Local models can run on them. Basically the way things work now is when you send a prompt to chat GPT or to Claude, it sends your prompt to the internet, to the servers that Claude or chat GPT are running on. A bunch of calculations are ran on those servers and then the response is sent back to you, right? So it's not happening locally, it's happening in the cloud. There are some disadvantages to that. Speed being one of them, privacy being another, all your prompts and all your responses are being saved on servers in the cloud so people who work for those companies can see what you're saying. Costs being another, you pay for every single token. So every single prompt you send and every single response you get back, that costs you money. It's basically like a toll boot. But when you run your models locally, instead of all those calculations happening on the cloud, on someone else's server, they're instead happening on your own devices, on your phone, on your computer, whatever it is. There are many advantages to this. One is it's completely free. If you're doing the calculations on your own computer, you're not paying for someone else to do the calculations, right? So it's completely free other than the cost of energy, right? Other than the cost of the power going into your computer. It's completely private. So the prompts you send, the responses you get, they stay on your computer. You don't even need to be connected to the internet to run these models It completely private and secure It unlimited 24 So the fact that it free unlocks all these new use cases that allow you to run models 24 365 right If you not paying for tokens, you can just have your AI calculating and doing things for you at all hours of the day, which is a big advantage. And lastly, education. You're learning a ton about AI by loading them locally, using them locally, seeing how they work. Just from an education perspective of learning how AI works, that's a massive advantage. A big one too I don't have here is just they can't change the models, they can't make them stupider, you're completely sovereign, they can't kick you off, they can't take it away from you, it's your model, it can never be taken away. It's like the bitcoin of AI models where you own your model, no one can change it, no one can take it away from you and those are some really big advantages. Now how do you run it? There's many different ways to do it. You can do it on Mac studios, Mac studios have a ton of memory, memory is the big thing here because when you load local AI models they get loaded into memory and so Macs have a really nice architecture where you get a ton of memory. Then you have Nvidia chips. Nvidia chips are really good and have their own advantages. They're really really fast, much faster than Mac but you don't get as much memory with them so you can't load quite as big models. So Mac devices you can load much bigger smarter models they're just a bit slower. Nvidia chips you run smaller models but they're much faster. On top of that you get some advantages to Nvidia where you can also fine-tune and train your own models so if that's something you're looking to do as well Nvidia chips are the way to go for that but those are your two options. I have both. I have a couple Mac studios and I have a DGX Spark which is what you see here. DGX Spark is probably the most popular way to run local models with Nvidia chips just because it's it's very much like a Mac where you don't have to kind of build your own computer you just buy one device plug it and it just works right away. So you want to decide what you want to do. If you just want to load local models and use them, Mac might be the way to go if speed not too important for you If you want to get like super advanced fine tune your own models train your own models then you might want to consider an NVIDIA device The more memory you get with each the bigger the models you can run right So if you get a Mac Studio, you know, you can get away with getting a 64 gig or 128 gig Mac Studio and run really, really good models. I have a 512 gig just because I'm crazy and I want the maximum power available to me. But you can get away with 64 or 128 if you want to run really powerful models. Now listen, you can go even smaller than that if you want. If you want to go 32 gigabyte, you can do that. You're just gonna be loading smaller models, right? They're not gonna be quite as smart. They're not gonna be able to handle quite as complex challenges or tasks, but that's fine. You know, there's nothing wrong with that and I think over time as we go, smarter models will fit with smaller footprints. You'll be able to run better and better models as time goes on. Now which models can you run? There's so many different models. If you're debating which one you can run, go to your OpenClaw and say, here's how much memory I have. Here's the device I have. Which models can I run with this hardware that I have? And your OpenClaw will be able to tell you. Again, if you don't have a ton of memory, you're not going to be able to run as smart models. But even if you can run a dumb model, there's still going to be advantages to that, right? The way I like to think about it is right now as of recording, you're still probably going to want to use cloud models. So Chad GPT or Claude as your orchestrator, as your high level brain of your open claw. But what you can do is you can start replacing muscles with local models. For instance, I use Quen 3.5 for coding. For a lot of my coding, I use Quen 3.5. That's a local model I'm running on my Mac Studio. Now, if you're running a much smaller device with only a little bit of memory, maybe you don't replace coding. Maybe you still use a cloud model for code for coding, but you use the local model for scraping online finding data online doing research online, right? So depending on your device, you can do much bigger tasks much bigger muscles with local models like coding But if you only have like 32 gigabytes or smaller Maybe you only do writing your research with the local models because that a lot less compute intensive So how do you set this up Your OpenClaw can pretty much handle it all for you OpenClaw did it for me I said hey load Quen It found the right website to go to, found the right model, loaded it on my computer. A really easy way to do this if you want a visual editor is LM Studio. It's completely free. You can download it and you can search for models there and you can see what modelers are available. Download them and load them very easily. If you ever get confused along the way, you can just ask your open claw how to do it and it will handle it for you. But I think local models are the future. I see a future where everyone - it's not even just the orchestrator that's cloud. You're going to have local models doing everything and not a single piece of your AI stack will be going to the cloud. And you'll be basically a sovereign individual that no one can take their super intelligence away from. I think this is something that's important to experiment with now. I'm experimenting with it now. I have a bunch of Mac studios and a DJX Spark. You don't need all that. Again, you can even have a Mac mini and run local models. It will be genius level. Probably not, but you can start offloading some of your tasks, which will save you money and also just educate you on the technology. So those are local models. I hope this is helpful. Let me know if you have any questions on this. I think it's worth everyone experimenting with. I think you'll be ahead of the pack, ahead of the group, especially if you can start setting up some more advanced use cases, Just as an example of an advanced use case, I have Quen 3.5, which is my local model, every 20 minutes going online and reading Reddit and X for challenges people have so that I can build out apps to solve those challenges. That's something you wouldn't be able to do with a cloud model because it'd be really expensive running ChatGPT every 20 minutes and searching the web for you. It would just get really expensive. But because I have local models, I can just continuously run this over and over and over and over again and not have to worry about costs. Those are the types of advanced use cases and workflows that unlock with local models. So you want to be taking advantage of them. Hope it was helpful. I'll see you in the next module.\r\ndocs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Mission Control\\lesson-notes.md:12: Mission Control is a fully custom web dashboard built and maintained by your OpenClaw agent. It serves as a centralized hub for all custom tooling, applications, analytics, and workflows. The key insight: you do not need to code anything yourself -- your OpenClaw builds and maintains the entire dashboard via natural language prompts.\r\ndocs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Mission Control\\lesson-notes.md:19: - Built entirely from scratch by your OpenClaw agent (not a pre-made template).\r\ndocs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Mission Control\\lesson-notes.md:34: - Tasks move along the board as the agent progresses through them.\r\ndocs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Mission Control\\lesson-notes.md:45: - Solves the problem of not having visual confirmation when the agent says \"I've scheduled that.\"\r\ndocs\\KnowledgeBase\\AlexFinn\\Mission Control\\lesson-notes.md:46: - Critical for trust and oversight -- you can verify the agent actually scheduled what it said it would."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":612,"aggregated":"docs\\00_CONTEXT.md:9: 2. Nao replicar processos - APRIMORAR (agentes fazem melhor que humanos em tarefas repetitivas)\r\ndocs\\00_CONTEXT.md:10: 3. SaaS entrega ferramenta ($1). Agent as a Service entrega RESULTADO ($6)\r\ndocs\\00_CONTEXT.md:19: 2. O primeiro case de Agents as a Service (documentado como case replicavel)\r\ndocs\\00_CONTEXT.md:70: - Agente \"Tobias\" criado como CEO do departamento de edicao\r\ndocs\\00_CONTEXT.md:75: - AGENTS.md boot sequence actualizado\r\ndocs\\00_CONTEXT.md:81: - Sub-agentes: ~/.openclaw/agents/<agentId>/agent/\r\ndocs\\00_CONTEXT.md:86: - 14 aulas Matt Ganzak digeridas (Security, Multi-agent, Skills, Platform, Cron, Sessions, Tokens, SEO, HeyGen, UGC, Prompt Caching, Update, Autonomous SaaS, Mission Control)\r\ndocs\\00_CONTEXT.md:98: 7. Criar agentes no OpenClaw (PM + VO) e copiar ficheiros\r\ndocs\\00_CONTEXT.md:100: 9. Configurar Telegram Topics para routing por agente\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:7: OpenClaw foi escolhido como framework de agentes. Razoes:\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:12: - Per-agent reasoning controls (modelos diferentes por agente)\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:22: - **Per-agent reasoning controls:** modelo diferente por agente\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:38: - Agentes so acedem a `auto_content_factory/` e `content_factory_v3/output/`\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:41: - API keys via KMS (ja centralizado, nao expostas aos agentes)\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:49: | O que e | Runtime de agentes (o funcionario) | Orquestrador (a empresa) |\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:50: | Multi-agent | Sub-agent spawning | Org charts, hierarquias, reporting |\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:51: | Budget | Agent-level | Per-agent monthly budgets, atomico |\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:52: | Agent-agnostic | Nao (e o agente) | Sim (OpenClaw, Claude Code, scripts, webhooks) |\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:55: - Skip para agora (overkill com <5 agentes)\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:56: - Considerar quando escalar para 5+ agentes com governance\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:62: | Microsoft Agent Framework | Ecossistema Microsoft, menos comunidade indie |\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:63: | Claude Agent SDK | Locked to Anthropic, nao suporta local models |\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:71: - @VadimStrizheus: agente 24/7 que clippa, agenda e posta videos\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:74: - Multi-machine: 5 agentes em 3 maquinas com permission model (per @cmd_alt_ecs)\r\ndocs\\01_FRAMEWORK_RESEARCH.md:75: - 6 agentes 24/7 com custom skills (per @TechWith_Nova)\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:7: O Lucca propos substituir o workflow engessado por uma equipa de agentes com liberdade editorial. Pontos-chave:\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:14: - Distribui trabalho para os branches abaixo\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:16: ### Branch 1 - Audio\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:23: ### Branch 2 - Dataset / Pesquisa de Imagens\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:24: - Agentes especialistas por tipo: pessoas, objectos, locais, eventos\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:30: ### Branch 3 - Direccao de Cena\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:31: - Recebe relatorio do Branch 2 + cenas + audios do Branch 1\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:35: - Coordena com Branch 2 para verificar se ja existe algo util\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:37: ### Branch 4 - Geracao de Imagens IA\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:41: ### Branch 5 - Edicao (Remotion)\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:48: > \"Ter mais branches com mais agentes e melhor do que menos. Depois retira-se. E melhor ter mais do que menos, principalmente no inicio.\"\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:60: Alguns branches do Lucca misturam as duas:\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:79: #### Camada 2 - Agentes de Decisao Editorial\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:81: **1. Scene Director Agent**\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:86: **2. Visual Research Planner Agent**\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:91: **3. Asset Finder Agents (subagentes operacionais)**\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:99: **4. Asset Judge Agent**\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:104: **5. AI Image Director Agent**\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:109: **6. Scene Composer Agent**\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:115: **7. Typography / Lettering Agent**\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:119: **8. Music & SFX Agent**\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:123: **9. QA / Coherence Agent**\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:124: - OBRIGATORIO - sem ele, multiagente vira delirio\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:130: 2. **Julgamento comparativo** - agente escolhe entre opcoes, nao inventa do zero\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:138: 3. Um agente por ferramenta (fragmentacao burra)\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:139: 4. Um superagente editor (impossivel de depurar)\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:145: 3. **Composicao de cena** - agente decide ordem, duracao, movimentos, overlays\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:154: | Branches | 5 (audio, dataset, direccao, geracao, edicao) | 9 agentes + camada deterministica |\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:155: | Separacao plan/exec | Misturados em alguns branches | Separados explicitamente |\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:157: | Criatividade | \"Dar liberdade aos agentes\" | \"Liberdade dentro de faixas\" |\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:159: | QA | Nao mencionado | Agente obrigatorio |\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:164: 1. Estrutura de branches do Lucca (mais granular, mais agentes)\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:168: 5. QA obrigatorio como ultimo agente\r\ndocs\\02_GPT_BRAINSTORM_ANALYSIS.md:169: 6. Per-agent model routing\r\ndocs\\03_PIPELINE_MAP.md:16: | **Divisao em cenas (Screenplay Agent)** | **CREATIVE** | parallel_screenplay.py (GPT-4.1-mini) |\r\ndocs\\03_PIPELINE_MAP.md:77: | Phase 5 | TSX validation + auto-fix | DETERMINISTIC + CREATIVE (fix agent) |\r\ndocs\\03_PIPELINE_MAP.md:92: ## Operacoes CREATIVE (candidatas a agentes)\r\ndocs\\05_MULTI_MACHINE_ARCHITECTURE.md:6: - **M1**: OpenClaw completo (Gateway + control plane + web UI + agentes)\r\ndocs\\05_MULTI_MACHINE_ARCHITECTURE.md:19: 1. Agente no M1 decide: \"preciso gerar 80 imagens para video X\"\r\ndocs\\05_MULTI_MACHINE_ARCHITECTURE.md:27: - O \"peso\" e nos agentes LLM - mas esses sao API calls (Gemini, OpenAI), nao compute local\r\ndocs\\05_MULTI_MACHINE_ARCHITECTURE.md:41: - @TechWith_Nova: 6 agentes 24/7 num unico OpenClaw\r\ndocs\\06_MODEL_STRATEGY.md:5: ### Main Agent (Orquestrador + conversacao)\r\ndocs\\06_MODEL_STRATEGY.md:7: - **Razao:** melhor custo-beneficio para agente principal 24/7, sem billing por token\r\ndocs\\06_MODEL_STRATEGY.md:10: ### Sub-agentes (tarefas especificas)\r\ndocs\\06_MODEL_STRATEGY.md:28: | ChatGPT Pro (main agent) | $200/mo |\r\ndocs\\06_MODEL_STRATEGY.md:29: | Anthropic API (sub-agentes quando necessario) | ~$50/mo |\r\ndocs\\06_MODEL_STRATEGY.md:38: - Claude fica como opcao para sub-agentes via API key\r\ndocs\\07_BRAINDUMP_OPENCLAW.md:19: O sistema actual funciona assim: para cada conta, um humano (eu, Lucca, junto com o Claude Code) configurou uma �nica vez todo o estilo de edi��o - quais prompts os agentes de IA usam, que tipo de imagens s�o geradas, que estilo de lettering aparece, que tipo de m�sica toca, como as cenas s�o compostas. Depois dessa configura��o, o pipeline gera v�deos automaticamente para diferentes scripts e temas.\r\ndocs\\07_BRAINDUMP_OPENCLAW.md:23: Hoje temos agentes de IA dentro do pipeline - eles dividem cenas, escolhem imagens, planeiam m�sica. Mas esses agentes seguem instru��es fixas definidas nos prompts. N�o tomam decis�es criativas verdadeiras. N�o adaptam o estilo baseado no conte�do. N�o pensam \"esta cena pede algo diferente\".\r\ndocs\\07_BRAINDUMP_OPENCLAW.md:27: O objectivo final � ter uma equipa de agentes aut�nomos que funcionem como um time real de editores de v�deo - onde cada v�deo tem o seu pr�prio processo criativo �nico. Agentes que:\r\ndocs\\07_BRAINDUMP_OPENCLAW.md:98: Estou a desenvolver a documenta��o e arquitectura para transformar o departamento de edi��o de v�deo num sistema aut�nomo de agentes. Este trabalho est� a ser feito em conjunto com o Claude Code (Anthropic), que roda nesta mesma m�quina e tem acesso aos mesmos ficheiros.\r\ndocs\\07_BRAINDUMP_OPENCLAW.md:104: O objectivo � definir uma hierarquia de agentes especializados - cada um com papel, modelo de IA e ferramentas espec�ficas - que consigam operar o departamento de edi��o de v�deo com cada vez mais autonomia e criatividade.\r\ndocs\\07_BRAINDUMP_OPENCLAW.md:108: - Tu (agente principal): actualmente em Sonnet 4.6 via API Key Anthropic. Ap�s o onboarding, migraremos para GPT-5.4 via ChatGPT Pro OAuth.\r\ndocs\\07_BRAINDUMP_OPENCLAW.md:109: - Sub-agentes simples: modelos locais via Ollama (Qwen 3.5 9B, Qwen3 14B) - custo $0\r\ndocs\\07_BRAINDUMP_OPENCLAW.md:110: - Sub-agentes que precisam de qualidade: Claude Sonnet/Opus via API key Anthropic, ou modelos custo-eficientes via OpenRouter (DeepSeek, MiniMax, Gemini Flash, entre outros - dependendo da tarefa)\r\ndocs\\07_BRAINDUMP_OPENCLAW.md:126: Baseado em tudo o que sabes sobre mim e sobre a Content Factory, o que mais precisas saber para me ajudar a transformar este departamento num sistema aut�nomo de agentes?\r\ndocs\\08_SECURITY_HARDENING.md:207: 1. **\"Eu uso zero skills de terceiros. O meu agente roda com skills que EU fiz.\"**\r\ndocs\\08_SECURITY_HARDENING.md:227: - Snyk Labs: \"Escaping the Agent: On Ways to Bypass OpenClaw's Security Sandbox\"\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:11: Agentes n�o s�o c�digo. S�o:\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:14: - Cada agente com papel, modelo e ferramentas espec�ficas\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:15: - Comunica��o entre agentes via artefactos estruturados (JSON, markdown)\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:16: - **Isolamento de contexto**: cada agente s� carrega os .md da sua pasta\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:33: ��� agents/\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:60: �       �   ��� agents/\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:71: �       �   ��� agents/\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:80: �       �   ��� agents/\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:90: �       �   ��� AGENTS.md\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:94: �       �   ��� agents/\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_AND_STRUCTURE.md:109: �       �   ��� agents/\r\ndocs\\09_HIERARCHY_A